<subSubSection id="19E465030A25D65EA0C9D1E4FAD6258E" pageId="20" pageNumber="421" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="514136880A25D65EA0C9D1E4FAD6258E" blockId="20.[151,1436,402,1758]" pageId="20" pageNumber="421">
<emphasis id="638AEA9A0A25D65EA0C9D1E4FEAF25EB" bold="true" box="[199,334,1699,1723]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="421" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis id="638AEA9A0A25D65EA349D1E4FC3F25EB" box="[839,990,1699,1723]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="421">lophacanthus</emphasis>
(= having a cluster of spines), referring to the dorsal lobe of the costal process having a cluster of dense thick spines at apex in the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
